The KIPP Foundation's Postsecondary Success Bridge Fund Program!

The KIPP Foundation is continuing to invest in our students and alumni through our Postsecondary Success Bridge Fund program. This Fund is designed to support alumni who, as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic, are experiencing financial hardship that could prohibit their enrolling or persisting in their chosen postsecondary education or training program. The funding to KIPP regions is to support students with tuition and fees, travel costs, course materials and technology, and physical/mental health support that has become necessary due to the pandemic. We want to make sure we don’t let this pandemic keep our alumni from realizing their dreams.

For more information and a link to the online application, contact Ms. Smitherman at msmitherman@kippenc.org.

post_text:
Today and always through our mission and commitment to a more just world, KIPP ENC honors the life and legacy of Congressperson John Lewis.

He showed us how to stand up for what’s right, how to march in solidarity with and for those demanding better of their country, and how to advocate fiercely for a more just nation and world. It’s our hope that the light he sparked with his words, deeds, and life will forever shine brightly in our students and staff.

Let us all rededicate ourselves today to causing all sorts of what he lovingly referred to as “good trouble.”

Rest in power, Congressperson Lewis.

post_text:
Mr. Allen, If you could be any animal, what would you be and why?
If I could be any animal I would be a Lion. Lions represent courage, authority and order. Lions are also family oriented and selfless. Additionally, the lionesses, like in my culture, are the true strength and agents of cohesiveness that keep the family thriving.

Mr. Allen, who inspires you?
Charlie Allen, Joseph Green, Cornell West, Dr. Umar Johnson, Dr. Doretha Allen, James Baldwin, Strong Black Brothers and Sistas all over the world.

Mr. Allen, what is your favorite book?
Babylon to Timbuktu by Rudolph R. Windsor

Mr. Allen, why is education important?
Education is important because it serves as a catalyst for opportunity. While much of the world struggles to embrace diversity, education continues to be the vehicle that consistently affords a marginalized people opportunities that otherwise may not have been offered.
GCP Primary School, HCP Primary School, GCP Middle School, KIPP Pride High School, KIPP Durham College Prep

Scholarships for High School and College Students!

Over the last few months, students and schools have faced significant challenges from distance learning and national tragedies. Times like these highlight how a great education is the most important asset a student can have to effectively change the world!

So here’s a question:

How has your school delivered on the promise of equal access and educational excellence, particularly during these challenging times?

Show us your answer with a brief video. Tell us how well your school did—or didn’t do—in providing you a great education and you’ll have a chance to win either one of ten $2,500 scholarships to the high school or college of your choice or the Grand Prize of a $20,000 scholarship to the high school or college of your choice! The World is Listening!

Visit MyEducationVidea.com to get started!

Beginning this year and moving forward, KIPP ENC will honor Juneteenth as an official holiday. As schools built on a mission to fight for social justice and aspiring to become anti-racist in all we do, this is an important position for us to take.

In the coming weeks and months, we'll gather input from our staff, students, and alumni about other ways we can celebrate this important day in our country's history while honoring it as a holiday.

Today, we celebrate freedom while fully acknowledging the fight for equality remains. ⁣

Background on Juneteenth: On June 19th 1865, enslaved African Americans were notified of their freedom by Union troops in Galveston Bay, TX. This notification came more than two years after the Emancipation Proclamation was issued and more than 2 months after the end of the Civil War on April 9, 1865.

post_text:
Whether we are teachers, parents, staff members, students, board members, alumni, leaders, volunteers or members of our broader community, our commitment to justice, should compel us all to do everything in our power to make sure the rights of all humans are respected, valued and protected. We should replace our privilege with proximity so that we can be close enough to those most directly affected to listen, to comfort, and to fight by their sides with our words and our actions.

All of us should be willing to do more than say we fight for social justice, we must be courageous enough to stand up, especially when it’s most inconvenient or unpopular, and support our students, our families, and staff members of color to let them know how much they are loved and how much their lives matter.

It is out of unconditional love, an unwavering commitment to justice, and the will to speak up and act that we truly fight to make our world a better, safer, more just place for people of color across our communities and our country.

post_text:
Dear KIPP ENC Families,

Welcome to the month of May! We hope April brought you and your family a safe and restful Spring Break, followed by more communication and support from your child’s teachers and more practice for your child to engage in remote learning. While school buildings will remain closed through the end of the school year, our remote learning will continue. Your child’s teacher(s) will continue to be in touch regularly to update you on remote learning plans and to make sure your child is accessing instruction each day. Your child’s teacher(s) will continue to be your best point of contact for any questions you or your child may have.

See the link below to read the Family Communication in its entirety.

https://kippenc.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/05/Family-Communication-05.06.20.pdf

Be Safe,
KIPP ENC

post_text:
MEET KIPP ENC LEADERS!

Introducing KIPP Durham College Preparatory School Leader Leonard Muhammad!

Mr. Muhmamad, what is your secret talent?
“I am a sneaky good cook. I just learned how to make Jamaican brown stew chicken!”

Why do you do this work?
“I do this work because it was a single experience in school that changed the trajectory of my own life as a young Black boy growing up in Baltimore. My belief is that if our babies have access to excellent education, we as a people can provide solutions to many of our own problems.”

What is the most joyful part of your job?
“I enjoy watching our students achieve heights that sometimes they don’t even think are possible. And I love to see the joy and relief that their success brings to their parents. It’s an awesome feeling.”

Learn more at www.kippenc.org!
